<div class="wrapper">

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">What is freestyle footbag?</h2>
    <p>
      Freestyle footbag is a movement discipline. Players keep a small bag in
      the air with their feet and link contacts and movements into sequences:
      catches, circles of the leg around the bag, spins, and jumps, all while
      the bag traces an unbroken path through the air.
    </p>
    {{#if content.demoVideo}}
    <figure class="demo-video">
      <video autoplay loop muted playsinline preload="metadata" poster="{{content.demoVideo.posterUrl}}">
        <source src="{{content.demoVideo.mp4Url}}" type="video/mp4">
        <p>{{content.demoVideo.caption}}</p>
      </video>
      <figcaption>{{content.demoVideo.caption}}</figcaption>
    </figure>
    {{/if}}
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">What you need</h2>
    <p>
      A footbag (any small, soft, slightly under-filled bag works to start),
      flat-soled shoes with a usable toe and inside surface, and a small clear
      space. That is all.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Begin with contact and control</h2>
    <p>
      Your first goal is simple: touch the bag and make it go where you want.
      Drop the bag from your hands onto the top of your foot near the toes,
      the <strong>toe surface</strong>, and kick it gently straight up. Catch
      it in your hands. Then try the <strong>inside surface</strong>: the flat
      inner edge of the shoe, kicking across your body's centre. When you can
      pop the bag up and catch it five times in a row from each surface, you
      have the two contacts most of freestyle is built on.
    </p>
    <p class="text-muted fs-sm">
      One term for later: a <strong>clipper</strong> is a particular use of the
      inside surface, catching the bag on the inside of the foot crossed behind
      the other leg. It is not another word for an ordinary inside kick; it
      comes later, once basic contacts feel comfortable.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Learn a stall</h2>
    <p>
      A <strong>stall</strong> (also called a <strong>delay</strong>) is
      catching the bag flat on a surface so it comes to rest instead of
      bouncing away. This is the skill freestyle is built on. Start with the
      toe stall: drop the bag from your hand, meet it with the top of your
      foot, and lower your foot as the bag lands to absorb its fall, like
      catching an egg. When the bag rests on your shoe, you have your first
      stall.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Set and catch</h2>
    <p>
      A <strong>set</strong> sends the bag upward; a <strong>catch</strong>
      regains control, usually as a stall. Tricks happen between those two
      moments. Exercise: from a toe stall, pop the bag up about head height
      with the same foot, let it fall, and stall it again. Every trick you ever
      learn will live inside that loop.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">What is a dexterity?</h2>
    <p>
      A <strong>dexterity</strong> (players say "dex") happens when a leg
      circles around the bag while it is in the air. Set the bag up, circle
      your leg over or around it while it hangs, and regain control. The
      circling leg never touches the bag; the circle itself is the trick.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Your first named trick: the Mirage</h2>
    <p>
      The Mirage is the simplest complete dexterity trick: one leg circles the
      bag once, and the bag is caught on a toe stall. Set the bag up from a
      stall, swing your other leg over it as it rises and falls, and catch it
      on the toe. That whole movement is a Mirage, and it is the idea much of
      freestyle is built from.
    </p>
    <p>
      <a href="/media/browse?context=mirage" class="btn btn-outline">Watch a Mirage Clip</a>
      <a href="/freestyle/families/mirage" class="btn btn-outline">Read About the Mirage</a>
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Clipper control, then Butterfly</h2>
    <p>
      Many famous tricks end on the clipper, that behind-the-leg use of the
      inside surface. Practice a basic clipper stall next: cross one foot
      behind the other leg and catch the bag flat on its inside surface. Once
      that feels stable, the <a href="/freestyle/families/butterfly">Butterfly</a>
      is a classic example of linking the two skills: a dexterity that flows
      into a clipper catch across the body. It is a real step up from the
      Mirage, so treat it as something to grow into, not your immediate next
      trick.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">How trick names grow</h2>
    <p>
      Freestyle trick names are compositional: a spinning mirage adds a body
      spin to the mirage movement, and the name says exactly that. Once you
      know a handful of movements, you can read most trick names before you
      have ever seen the trick performed.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Where to go next</h2>
    <p>
      Practice the loop: stall on both feet, then the Mirage in both
      directions. When you want more,
      <a href="/media/freestyle-tutorials">the tutorial collections</a> hold
      lesson videos for dozens of tricks. When you are curious how it all fits
      together:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><a href="/freestyle/learn">Learn the movement vocabulary</a>: guided lessons and progressions.</li>
      <li><a href="/freestyle/tricks">Look up a trick</a>: the full dictionary.</li>
      <li><a href="/freestyle/glossary">Understand a term</a>: plain-language definitions.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

</div>
